[5] Ecuador
Date: Mon 19 Dec 2011
Source: Univision Noticia [In Spanish, trans. by JG, edited by mods
JG/CP]]
http://feeds.univision.com/feeds/article/2011-12-18/brote-de-sarampion-en-ecuador

169 confirmed cases since July
--------------------------
The Health Ministry repored on Sunday [18 Dec 2011] that the outbreak
of measles which began in Ecuador in July [2011] has resulted in 169
confirmed cases, 131 of whom were in the Andean province of
Tungurahua, predominatly amon the indigeneous poulation.

The disease is currently affecting six of the 24 Ecuadorian provinces,
including Pichincha (where Quito, the capital City of Ecuador is
located), where 14 cases had been reported, according to the Ministry
of Health. No deaths related with this outbreak have been reported.

The Health Authorities also stated that there had been 10 cases in
Guayas province (southwestern part of the country), 8 in Cotopaxi, and
3 in Chimborazo (both in southern Ecuador), and 3 additional cases in
Pastaza (southeast, near the Peruvian border).

The Ministry of Health, who constricted a rigoous vaccination campaign
having immunized nearly 3.4 million children and teenagers, has
reported 1207 cases of measles up to last October.

The epidemiological surveillance system is still in a state of alert
because suspected cases of measles have been reported in the Kapawi
indigenous community in Pastaza province in the Amazon region, and the
population has been advised to avoid travelling to reduse running the
risk of spreading the virus.

Ecuadorian Health Minister, David Chiriboga, said that the measles
outbreak was cause by a geneotypB3 virus which has been prevalent in
Africa and the United Statesthat was probaly introduced into Ecuador
by someone who had travelled abroad.to the country with someone who
traveled to abroad ".

